Data Dictionary for Child Care example

The IHDP intervention was implemented in the 1980âs and targeted low
birth weight (less than 2500 grams), pre-term children.  They were
recruited at the time of birth.  It provided high quality child care
and other services in their first 3 years of life.  The comparison
group was pulled from a survey conducted during the same time period
called the National Survey of Longitudinal Youth.  At the time of the
intervention many of the original survey participants (first recruited
in 1979) had children. We have data from those children and their
mothers for an overlapping set of variables (below) as the IHDP
children.

The intervention for low-birth-weight children is described by
- Brooks-Gunn, J., Liaw, F. R., and Klebanov, P. K. (1992). Effects of
  early intervention on cognitive function of low birth weight preterm
  infants. Journal of Pediatrics 120, 350â359.
- Hill, J. L., Brooks-Gunn, J., and Waldfogel, J. (2003). Sustained
  effects of high participation in an early intervention for
  low-birth-weight premature infants. Developmental Psychology 39,
  730â744.

Data columns

"momage"   
mom age at time of birth

"b.marr"   
indicator for whether mom was married at birth

"momed"    
motherâs education level at the time she gave birth

"work.dur" 
indicator for whether mom worked in the year before she gave birth

"prenatal" 
indicator for whether mom received prenatal care

"cig"     
 indicator for whether mom smoked cigarettes while pregnant

"booze"    
indicator for whether mom drank alcohol while pregnant

"sex"      
indicator for whether child was born male or female

"first"    
indicator for whether child was the first born for the mother

"bw"       
childâs birth weight

"bwg"      
indicator for whether child was born low birth weight

"preterm" 
number of weeks preterm child was born

"black", "hispanic", "white"    
indicators for childâs race/ethnicity

"lths", "hs", "ltcoll", "college"  
indicators for motherâs education at time of birth

"dayskidh" 
number of days child was in the hospital after being born

"st5", "st9", "st12", "st25", "st36", "st42", "st48", "st53"    
indicator for state where household resides 

"st99"  
indicator for whether family  was living in state served by the ihdp

"income"   
family income one year after the child was born

"treat"   
indicator for whether family was allowed to receive IHDP services (1 = yes) 

"ppvtr.36"
IQ measured at age 36 months

love_plot <- function(x) {
  love.plot(x,
            binary = "std",
            stats = c("m", "ks"),
            thresholds = c(.1, .05)) ## will draw a line at .1 for std dev eventually
}

8.1.1 Exercise

Gelman & colleagues decided to omit babies with the lowest birth weights (â¤ 1500 g) because they were too different from the comparison group. I suppose these extreme low birth weight babies (who hopefully received treatment) did not have matches in the control (untreated) group. Thus, these extremely low birth weights are outside the region of common support. The main problem is that dropping these cases could bias our estimates- likely by underestimating the true treatment effect.

While it would be tempting to exclude them, especially if I wanted to calculate an ATE, It would be best to include them. I want to maintain as much information possible about these extreme cases, especially if they did receive treatment. Otherwise, our estimates might be smaller than the true effect.

We can see below that the distribution of birth weights are very different for treatment/control groups. Since birthweight affects selection into treatment, Iâd want to account for that in estimating a treatment effect.

ggplot(data = d, 
       aes(x = bw, fill = as.factor(treat)) ) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3) + 
  theme_light()

Our naive estimate is:

mean(d$ppvtr.36[d$treat==1]) - mean(d$ppvtr.36[d$treat==0])
[1] 6.08574

Receiving the treatment increases test score by 6.09 points. But this assumes there is no difference between treatment and control groups (other than treatment), and we know thatâs not the case.

8.1.2 Exercise

Explicit targets of treatment (low birth weight, living in state where treatment occurs):

  • Low birth weight vars (bw, bwg) and premature var (preterm)

  • variables related to location: st5, st9, st12, st25, st36, st42, st48, st53, st99

Maternal & environmental characteristics that could affect both birthweight (which in turn affects selection into treatment) & our outcome IQ variable:

  • momage, b.marr, momed (and/or series of indicators for momâs education: lths, hs, ltcoll, college), work.dur, prenatal, cig, booze, income

Other child characteristics that could affect selection into treatment & outcome variable:

  • sex, first, black, hispanic, white, dayskidh

You can see my different attempts at formulas that âwork.â

Interestingly, entropy balancing does not work until version #5.

Hereâs the logic of what I ended up including:

  • Preterm would not balance, neither would the gram measure of birth weight (bw). I included only the binary measure of low birth weight (bw) to predict selection into treatment.

    • I also include only the st99 residence variable, which also affects selection into treatment.

  • I keep momâs age in as a quadratic term. I also keep her marital status. I found the categorical momed difficult to balance, and returned back to four dummy variables for education. (Perhaps making momed into a factor variable would have done this task as well.) I also keep information to if mom worked during pregnancy, the number of prenatal visits, and family income.

  • I keep babyâs sex, if baby is first born, and race of baby.

  • What other variables are omitted?

    • all state variables other than st99 (for simplicity)

    • cig and booze and dayskidh are omitted, largely due to inability to balance.

trt_form_1 <- "treat ~ bw + bwg + preterm + 
                     st5 + st9 + st12 + st25 + st36 + st42 + st48 + st53 + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + lths + hs + ltcoll + college + 
                     work.dur + prenatal + cig + booze + income +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white + dayskidh"

trt_form_2 <- "treat ~ bw + bwg + preterm + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + lths + hs + ltcoll + college + 
                     work.dur + prenatal + cig + booze + income +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white + dayskidh"

trt_form_3 <- "treat ~ bw + preterm + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + momed + 
                     work.dur + prenatal + cig + booze + income +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white"

trt_form_4 <- "treat ~ bw + bwg + preterm + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + momed + 
                     work.dur + prenatal + income +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white"

trt_form_5 <- "treat ~ bw + bwg + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + momed + 
                     work.dur + prenatal  +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white" ## FIRST TIME EBAL WORKS

trt_form_6 <- "treat ~ bwg + st99 +
                     momage + I(momage^2) + b.marr + lths + hs + ltcoll + college +
                     work.dur + prenatal  + income +
                     sex + first + black + hispanic + white"
